description.plain: On the title track of her debut album, Stella Donnelly widens the scope of her storytelling to a broader, but no less pressing issue – the cultural and environmental destruction of Australia by its own government.

body.plain: On the title track of her debut album, Stella Donnelly widens the scope of her storytelling to a broader, but no less pressing issue – the cultural and environmental destruction of Australia by its own government.

annotations:
There’s an architect setting fire to her house
 All the plans were there, but they built it inside out
An analogy for having good intentions but screwing up along the way.

My home, carpet on the stairs
 Everyone in bed, their eyes are white as clouds
 Next door, sounds like bloody war
 Waiting for the phone, telling us to run

Waiting to fall asleep and overhearing your neighbours arguing is commonplace in Australia,

[According to White Ribbon Australia one in four women have experienced emotional abuse on behalf of a partner since the age of fifteen ]
(https://www.whiteribbon.org.au/understand-domestic-violence/facts-violence-women/domestic-violence-statistics/)

All the painted little gnomes
 Smiling in a line, tryna get your votes

The “painted little gnomes” highlight the difference in how the politicians represent themselves, versus how they are seen by the public (like the “beast that doesn’t know its face is frightening to behold”). It also compares these politicians to common garden gnomes, implying they are mass-produced, generic, and the same as one another.

The second line shows the difference between how elected officials act while campaigning versus after being elected into power – at first they are kind and make lots of promises to ensure they get votes, but once they are in power, we see their true intentions as highlighted by the chorus.
Beware of the dogs, beware of the dogs

Like George Orwell and Roger Waters before her, Stella invokes the use of animal imagery for the personification of human emotions, transforming the vicious greed of politicians into a personification of dogs.

“Beware of the dogs” is a phrase generically used as a warning or deterrent to keep unwanted intruders off property, and here Stella uses it as a warning to the general populace, to be wary of those in power that do not have good intentions.
No one will endure what the sign told them they would

Acknowledging that the older generations who caused the vast majority of environmental destruction will likely not be alive in the coming decades to have to endure the catastrophic effects of their willful ignorance.
Now we’ll all endure what the sign told us we would

Here, Stella inverts the prior instance of this lyric to reflect the present reality of the destruction that prior generations have cause to the environment – all that the younger generations will be able to do is watch and wonder why those that came before didn’t take action to protect them.
All these pious fucks taking from the 99

This recalls the Occupy movement’s well-known rallying cry, “We are the 99%”. Stella is frustrated with sanctimonious and hypocritical criticizing and stealing from the people, all while acting as though they are morally and socially superior to those they represent.
There’s no Parliament worthy of this countryside

Despite their posturing and moralizing, Stella emphasizes that the elected officials who lead her country are not any more entitled to it than its people – and that includes the responsibility to protect it from harm, rather than to damage and exploit it for their personal gain.

There’s an architect setting fire to her house
 All the plans were there, but they built it inside out

This could be interpreted to represent the destruction of Australia by the government and people who live there. The government of the country could be considered its “architect” in the sense of building and maintaining the country, and they are “setting fire” to Australia by exploiting its resources and native peoples.

Additionally, there’s an idea of willful stubbornness here – the proper “plans” were there for the house, yet it was still built “inside out”. This could represent the willful ignorance of facts,  like the abundant environmental issues of Australia that Stella feels passionate about. Environmental destruction issues are well-documented and alarming, yet there is a stubborn tendency to resist making changes to alleviate it.

This street is haunted like a beast
 That doesn’t know its face is frightening to behold

The “beast” could be a metaphor for government types that make empty promises to gain power over the people they claim to represent.  Their “face” is presented as one of compassion and championing the needs of the people, but our understanding of their true intentions makes it “frightening” – Stella is cynical to the promises the people leading her government make, and is rightly afraid of their misused power.

annotations: Southern Cross tattoo
see above

You’re always wanting a kiss and then you want to get laid
 Get laid, ah, get laid
This line is a subversion, the way this verse is lyrically set up you expect her to say “You want to get fucked”, but instead she says laid, its the same meaning but its a fun quirk to the song.
You’ve got all of your ducks lined up in a row
This is another way of saying that youve got your shit together, or more formally youre well organized.
You only like me when I do my tricks for you
As an artist Stella highlights the ways in which certain audiences view her work as a mere spectacle for their own enjoyment.
You wear me out like you wear that Southern Cross tattoo

The Southern Cross is an iconic constellation easily visible in the southern hemisphere. It is prominently featured on the Australian and Kiwi flags.



It also used to be a popular tattoo to display national pride in both these countries but just as Stella, they have gotten worn out.

The southern cross as a symbol has become more politically charged in Australia. It is now sometimes associated with racially motivated violence.
Kyle and Jackie O
The Kyle and Jackie O Show is an Australian breakfast radio show hosted by Kyle Sandilands and Jackie O on 96FM on weekdays from 6pm till 7pm.

body.plain: The song addresses the culture of victim blaming in relation to sexual assault.

annotations: Deaf to the word “no”
Stella affirms that boys are prompt into ignoring people’s boundaries, disrespecting if someone settles it with a ‘no’. In the song scenario, this is alluding to sorts of sexual assaults/rape.
Ou invaded her magnificence
After her friend was sexually assaulted, Stella noticed that her friend wasn’t the same as before. Her friend was perhaps traumatized after what had happened to her.
Put your hand over her mouth
This implies that the rapist not only physically subdued her, but also silenced her from speaking out after the fact.

”Why was she all alone
 Wearing her shirt that low?”

People often wrongly blame victims of sexual assault through asking what they were wearing at the time, this line is refering to that,

There was an exhibition called “What Were You Wearing” in which the clothing victims of sexual assault were wearing at the time is displayed in an attempt to change the misconception that clothing type is involved in the causation of sexual assault
[https://www.forestry.oregonstate.edu/wwyw/homepage#:~:text=What%20Were%20You%20Wearing%3F%20is,by%20Jen%20Brockman%20and%20Dr.&text=The%20OSU%20exhibit%20curators%20have,based%20on%20these%20survivors'%20experiences.]
They said, “Boys will be boys”

The term “boys will be boys” is idiomatic and is often used, as in this particular case, to justify egregious (sexual) behavior committed by men as simply a part of their nature.

This idea, as the title, sums up the objective of the song: pointing out the outlandishness of the means perpetuating rape culture– such as chalking up the act of sexual assault as inherent and beyond external accountability.

Like a mower in the morning
 I will never let you rest
 You broke all the bonds she gave ya
 Time to pay the fucking rent

She is now speaking to the rapist.
A “mower” is a lawn mower, which often you will be woken up by in the morning on a weekend – therefore not letting you sleep (“rest”).

Deaf to, deaf to
 Deaf to the word “no, no, no, no”
These lines are referencing consent (or lack thereof) in sexual activity, where, in incidents of rape, one party’s rejection of sexual advances is dismissed.

Your father told you that you’re innocent
 Told ya, “Women rape themselves”
 Would ya blame your little sister
 If she cried to you for help?

Donnelly directs the attention of the song to her friend’s rapist. Often, the blame of rape is pushed onto the victim, and the rapist himself is exonerated both socially and legally. The rapist’s father follows this traditional line of thought that it’s the woman’s fault for rape: she made herself vulnerable, and thus she got what she deserved.

Donnelly then weaponizes another member of the rapist’s family: a fellow female, the man’s sister, and asks him whether he’d place blame on some of his own blood for something clearly not her doing. If he wouldn’t, then the rapist also shouldn’t be totally absolved of his crime.

My friend told me of a secret
 Told me that she blames herself

Donnelly starts off the song with setting a scene in which one of her friends confides her a secret: somehow she feels as if it was her own fault she got raped.

This guilt is often instilled in survivers of sexual assault, for society tends to question them instead of their offenders: what were they wearing? Why weren’t they in company? Why were they out that late?

description.plain:
This is my attempt at building a song out of a very specific dynamic between two monogamously involved people. The verses are just excerpts from real conversations, fragments of what two people talk about when they both know they need to have a real talk but neither wants to be the one to bring it up. This song came out of lockdown and seeing a lot of friends break up or get married.

- Stella Donnelly on Stereogum
